 Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Newmarch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: locative name from Neufmarché (Seine-Maritime). See   Anglo-Norman Families  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Newmark","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Emanuel, Chayim, Meyer, Shlomo, Vigdor.","Americanized form of Scandinavian <b>Nymark</b>: habitational name from farms named with <i>ny</i> ‘new’ + <i>mark</i> ‘field’.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Neumark  ."]},{"name":"Anglo-Norman Families","meanings":["1  Norman, English: variant of   Matravers  .","2  Norman, English: locative name from Martinvast (in Manche, France). See   Anglo-Norman Families  ."]},{"name":"Newmarsh","meanings":["Norman:  see  Newmarch  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Newmarch was born in 1196, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Adam de Newmarch II, was 31 and his mother, Margeria de Bosville, was 23. He married Pernel de Wormersley about 1220, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1243, in his hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1196–1243":"8.jaanuar1196kuni7.jaanuar1197–1243","1096–1160":"1096–1160","1203–1303":"1203–1303","1226–1283":"1226–1283","1166–1247":"1166–1247","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","Abt 1226":"umbes 1226","1196":"8. jaanuar 1196 kuni 7. jaanuar 1197","1174":"1174","1283":"1283","1096":"1096","1160":"1160","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1243":"1243","1166":"1166","Womersley, Yorkshire, England":"Womersley, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Wormersley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1196–1243":"vuodesta8.tammikuuta1196vuoteen7.tammikuuta1197–1243","1096–1160":"1096–1160","1203–1303":"1203–1303","1226–1283":"1226–1283","1166–1247":"1166–1247","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","Abt 1226":"noin 1226","1196":"vuodesta 8. tammikuuta 1196 vuoteen 7. tammikuuta 1197","1174":"1174","1283":"1283","1096":"1096","1160":"1160","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","1224":"12